FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - MOZAMBIQUE (02): OIE SUSPECTED
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Fri, 08 Nov 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Weekly Disease Information, Fri 08 Nov, 2002 [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/a_info.htm>

Foot & mouth disease in Mozambique: suspected outbreak
-------------------------------------------------------
(Date of previous reported outbreak: 1985).
Emergency report
Information received on 07 Nov 2002 from Dr Adolfo Paulo Mavale, Head
of the Animal Health Department, Ministry of Agriculture, Maputo:
Report date: 06 Nov 2002.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 04 Nov 2002.
Estimated date of first infection: 20 Oct 2002.
Suspected outbreaks:
Location -- Calanga (25 deg 2 min 04.3 S - 32 deg 53 min 04.6 E),
Manhiça district, Maputo Province.
No. of outbreaks -- 1.
Description of affected population: Suspected clinical foot and mouth
disease has been detected in three kraals situated in an area with
communal grazing land.
Total number of animals in the suspected outbreak:
species/susceptible/cases/deaths/destroyed/slaughtered
bov/ 400 /20/ .../ .../ ...
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where samples were sent for confirmation of diagnosis:
Onderstepoort Veterinary Institute, South Africa.
B. Causal agent: SAT foot-and-mouth-disease virus suspected.
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: under investigation.
B. Other epidemiological details:
- Farmers report having bought 5 cattle from Chicualacuala district,
situated in the southwestern part of Mozambique close to the border
with Zimbabwe, some 20 days ago.
- No susceptible wildlife exists in the suspect area.
- Investigations are in progress to determine the extent of the disease.
Control measures:
- Manhiça district in the Maputo province has been placed under quarantine;
- movement control in the adjacent areas;
- vaccination of all cattle in the Manhiça district (8500 head
vaccinated) is being carried out and surveillance has been
intensified in this district.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[We have been notified by the Animal Health Information Department of
the OIE that an error has occurred in the submitted emergency report
from Mozambique concerning the estimated date of first infection,
which was not 20 Aug 2002 (as published earlier in the OIE alert
message 20021108.5751), but 20 Oct 2002. There are additional
changes and added information in this posting, compared to the
initial alert message. - Mod.AS]
